Project Overview\n\n### 2.1 Purpose\nTo develop a secure REST API that provides authentication capabilities and standard CRUD operations on resources, following RESTful principles and industry best practices for API design.\n\n### 2.2 Scope\nThe API will include:\n- User registration and authentication endpoints\n- JWT-based token authentication\n- Resource management with CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete)\n- Proper HTTP methods and status codes\n- Request/response validation\n- Authorization for protected endpoints\n\n### 2.3 Out of Scope (Phase 1)\n- OAuth2 or third-party authentication providers\n- GraphQL interface\n- WebSocket or real-time features\n- Advanced rate limiting and throttling\n- API versioning beyond v1\n- Caching layer\n\n---\n\n## 3. Functional Requirements\n\n### 4.1 Authentication System\n\n#### FR-AUTH-001: User Registration\n- System SHALL allow new users to create accounts\n- Required fields: email, password, username\n- Email addresses MUST be unique across the system\n- Passwords MUST meet minimum security standards (minimum 8 characters, at least one uppercase, one lowercase, one number)\n\n#### FR-AUTH-002: User Login\n- System SHALL authenticate users with email and password\n- System SHALL provide appropriate error messages for failed login attempts\n- System SHALL implement session management after successful login\n\n#### FR-AUTH-003: User Logout\n- System SHALL allow authenticated users to log out\n- System SHALL clear user session upon logout\n\n#### FR-AUTH-004: Password Security\n- System SHALL hash passwords before storage\n- System SHALL NOT store passwords in plain text\n- System SHALL implement secure password recovery mechanism\n\n#### FR-AUTH-005: Token Management\n- System SHALL generate JWT tokens upon successful authentication\n- Tokens SHALL include user ID, expiration time, and claims\n- System SHALL validate tokens on all protected endpoints\n- System SHALL reject expired or invalid tokens with appropriate HTTP status codes (401)\n\n### 4.2 Resource Management (CRUD Operations)\n\n#### FR-API-001: Create Resource\n- Authenticated users SHALL be able to create new resources via POST requests\n- System SHALL validate request payload against defined schema\n- System SHALL return 201 Created status with resource location\n- System SHALL assign unique identifier to each resource\n- Resources SHALL be associated with the authenticated user\n\n#### FR-API-002: Read Resources\n- Authenticated users SHALL retrieve their own resources via GET requests\n- System SHALL support retrieving individual resource by ID\n- System SHALL support retrieving collection of resources\n- Users SHALL NOT access resources belonging to other users\n- System SHALL return 404 for non-existent resources\n\n#### FR-API-003: Update Resource\n- Authenticated users SHALL update their resources via PUT or PATCH requests\n- System SHALL validate update payload\n- System SHALL return 200 OK with updated resource\n- System SHALL update last modified timestamp\n- Users SHALL only update their own resources\n\n#### FR-API-004: Delete Resource\n- Authenticated users SHALL delete their resources via DELETE requests\n- System SHALL return 204 No Content on successful deletion\n- System SHALL return 404 if resource doesn't exist\n- Deletion SHALL be permanent (no soft delete in Phase 1)\n- Users SHALL only delete their own resources\n\n#### FR-API-005: Resource Authorization\n- System SHALL enforce resource ownership on all operations\n- System SHALL return 403 Forbidden for unauthorized access attempts\n- System SHALL validate user authorization on every request\n\n---\n\n## 5. Non-Functional Requirements\n\n### 5.1 Security Requirements\n\n#### NFR-SEC-001: Data Protection\n- System SHALL use HTTPS for all communications\n- System SHALL protect against common vulnerabilities (SQL injection, XSS, CSRF)\n- System SHALL implement proper authentication and authorization checks\n\n#### NFR-SEC-002: Password Storage\n- System SHALL use industry-standard hashing algorithms (bcrypt, Argon2, or PBKDF2)\n- System SHALL implement salt for password hashing\n\n### 5.2 Performance Requirements\n\n#### NFR-PERF-001: Response Time\n- API endpoints SHALL respond within 200ms for simple queries\n- Complex operations SHALL complete within 1 second\n- Authentication endpoints SHALL respond within 300ms\n\n#### NFR-PERF-002: Scalability\n- System SHALL support at least 100 concurrent requests\n- Database SHALL efficiently handle at least 10,000 resources per user\n- API SHALL be horizontally scalable\n\n### 5.3 API Design Requirements\n\n#### NFR-API-001: RESTful Design\n- API SHALL follow REST architectural principles\n- Endpoints SHALL use appropriate HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT/PATCH, DELETE)\n- API SHALL use meaningful, resource-based URLs\n- API SHALL return appropriate HTTP status codes\n\n#### NFR-API-002: API Documentation\n- API SHALL provide OpenAPI 3.0 (Swagger) specification\n- All endpoints SHALL be documented with examples\n- Authentication requirements SHALL be clearly documented\n- Error responses SHALL be documented\n\n### 5.4 Reliability Requirements\n\n#### NFR-REL-001: Availability\n- API SHALL maintain 99% uptime\n- System SHALL handle errors gracefully without data loss\n- API SHALL provide meaningful error messages in JSON format\n\n#### NFR-REL-002: Data Integrity\n- System SHALL prevent data loss during transactions\n- System SHALL maintain data consistency\n- Database operations SHALL be atomic\n\n### 5.5 Maintainability Requirements\n\n#### NFR-MAIN-001: Code Quality\n- Code SHALL follow established coding standards\n- Code SHALL include appropriate inline documentation\n- System SHALL have modular, maintainable architecture\n- API SHALL have comprehensive logging\n\n#### NFR-MAIN-002: Testing\n- System SHALL have minimum 70% test coverage\n- All endpoints SHALL have integration tests\n- Critical paths SHALL have end-to-end tests\n\n---\n\n## 6. Technical Requirements\n\n### 6.1 API Endpoints\n- POST /api/v1/auth/register - User registration\n- POST /api/v1/auth/login - User authentication\n- POST /api/v1/auth/logout - User logout\n- GET /api/v1/resources - List resources\n- GET /api/v1/resources/:id - Get single resource\n- POST /api/v1/resources - Create resource\n- PUT/PATCH /api/v1/resources/:id - Update resource\n- DELETE /api/v1/resources/:id - Delete resource\n\n### 6.2 Request/Response Format\n- Content-Type: application/json\n- Accept: application/json\n- Authentication: Bearer token in Authorization header\n- Consistent error response structure\n\n### 6.3 Data Storage\n- Relational database (PostgreSQL, MySQL) or NoSQL (MongoDB)\n- User credentials table\n- Resources table with user relationship\n- Database connection pooling\n\n---\n\n## 7. Constraints\n\n### 7.1 Technical Constraints\n- Must use modern backend framework\n- Must implement JWT-based authentication\n- Must comply with data protection regulations (GDPR, CCPA)\n- Must use HTTPS for all communications\n\n### 7.2 Business Constraints\n- Phase 1 development timeline\n- Resource availability\n- Initial support for 100 concurrent users\n\n---\n\n## 8. (ERD)\n\n```\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502     users \u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n         \u2502\n         \u2502 1:N\n         \u2502\n         \u25bc\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502     todos       \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n\u2502 id (PK)         \u2502\n\u2502 user_id (FK)    \u2502\n\u2502 title           \u2502\n\u2502 description     \u2502\n\u2502 due_date        \u2502\n\u2502 priority        \u2502\n\u2502 completed       \u2502\n\u2502 created_at      \u2502\n\u2502 updated_at      \u2502\n\u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518\n```\n\n---\n\n## Table Definitions\n\n### 1. users Table\n\n**Purpose:** Store user account information\n\n**Table Structure:**\n\n| Column | Type | Constraints | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|-------------|\n| id | UUID | PRIMARY KEY, DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4() | Unique user identifier |\n| email | VARCHAR(255) | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | User email address |\n| username | VARCHAR(50) | NOT NULL | User display name |\n| password_hash | VARCHAR(255) | NOT NULL | Bcrypt hashed password |\n| created_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Account creation timestamp |\n| updated_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Last update timestamp |\n\n**Indexes:**\n- Primary Key: `id`\n- Unique Index: `email` (for fast lookup during login)\n- Index: `created_at` (for sorting/analytics)\n\n**PostgreSQL DDL:**\n```sql\nCREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS \"uuid-ossp\";\n\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n    email VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n    username VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,\n    password_hash VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\n    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),\n    updated_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n\n-- Create indexes\nCREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_users_email ON users(email);\nCREATE INDEX idx_users_created_at ON users(created_at DESC);\n\n-- Create trigger to auto-update updated_at\nCREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column()\nRETURNS TRIGGER AS $$\nBEGIN\n    NEW.updated_at = NOW();\n    RETURN NEW;\nEND;\n$$ language 'plpgsql';\n\nCREATE TRIGGER update_users_updated_at\n    BEFORE UPDATE ON users\n    FOR EACH ROW\n    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();\n```\n\n**Sample Data:**\n```sql\nINSERT INTO users (email, username, password_hash) VALUES\n('john@example.com', 'johndoe', '$2b$10$HASH_HERE'),\n('jane@example.com', 'janedoe', '$2b$10$HASH_HERE');\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. todos Table\n\n**Purpose:** Store TODO items for users\n\n**Table Structure:**\n\n| Column | Type | Constraints | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|-------------|\n| id | UUID | PRIMARY KEY, DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4() | Unique TODO identifier |\n| user_id | UUID | NOT NULL, FOREIGN KEY \u2192 users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE | Owner of the TODO |\n| title | VARCHAR(255) | NOT NULL | TODO title/summary |\n| description | TEXT | NULL | Detailed description |\n| due_date | TIMESTAMP | NULL | Optional due date |\n| priority | VARCHAR(10) | NOT NULL, DEFAULT 'medium', CHECK IN ('low','medium','high') | Priority level |\n| completed | BOOLEAN | NOT NULL, DEFAULT FALSE | Completion status |\n| created_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Creation timestamp |\n| updated_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Last update timestamp |\n\n**Indexes:**\n- Primary Key: `id`\n- Foreign Key: `user_id` \u2192 `users(id)`\n- Composite Index: `(user_id, completed)` (for filtering by user and status)\n- Index: `(user_id, created_at DESC)` (for sorted listing)\n- Index: `(user_id, due_date)` (for due date queries)\n\n**PostgreSQL DDL:**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE todos (\n    id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n    user_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\n    description TEXT,\n    due_date TIMESTAMP,\n    priority VARCHAR(10) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'medium' CHECK (priority IN ('low', 'medium', 'high')),\n    completed BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT FALSE,\n    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),\n    updated_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n\n-- Create indexes for efficient queries\nCREATE INDEX idx_todos_user_id ON todos(user_id);\nCREATE INDEX idx_todos_user_completed ON todos(user_id, completed);\nCREATE INDEX idx_todos_user_created_at ON todos(user_id, created_at DESC);\nCREATE INDEX idx_todos_user_due_date ON todos(user_id, due_date);\nCREATE INDEX idx_todos_user_priority ON todos(user_id, priority);\n\n-- Create trigger to auto-update updated_at\nCREATE TRIGGER update_todos_updated_at\n    BEFORE UPDATE ON todos\n    FOR EACH ROW\n    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();\n```\n\n**Sample Data:**\n```sql\nINSERT INTO todos (user_id, title, description, priority, completed) VALUES\n('user-uuid-1', 'Complete project documentation', 'Write comprehensive docs', 'high', false),\n('user-uuid-1', 'Review pull requests', 'Check team PRs', 'medium', false),\n('user-uuid-1', 'Buy groceries', 'Milk, bread, eggs', 'low', true);\n```\n\n---\n\n## Optional Tables (Future Enhancement)\n\n### 3. refresh_tokens Table (Optional)\n\n**Purpose:** Store refresh tokens for JWT authentication\n\n**Table Structure:**\n\n| Column | Type | Constraints | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|-------------|\n| id | UUID | PRIMARY KEY | Token identifier |\n| user_id | UUID | NOT NULL, FOREIGN KEY \u2192 users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE | Token owner |\n| token | VARCHAR(500) | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | Refresh token string |\n| expires_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL | Token expiration |\n| created_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Creation timestamp |\n| revoked | BOOLEAN | NOT NULL, DEFAULT FALSE | Revocation status |\n\n**PostgreSQL DDL:**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE refresh_tokens (\n    id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n    user_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    token VARCHAR(500) NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n    expires_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,\n    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),\n    revoked BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT FALSE\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_refresh_tokens_user_id ON refresh_tokens(user_id);\nCREATE INDEX idx_refresh_tokens_token ON refresh_tokens(token);\nCREATE INDEX idx_refresh_tokens_expires_at ON refresh_tokens(expires_at);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. sessions Table (Alternative to JWT)\n\n**Purpose:** Store server-side sessions\n\n**Table Structure:**\n\n| Column | Type | Constraints | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|-------------|\n| id | UUID | PRIMARY KEY | Session identifier |\n| user_id | UUID | NOT NULL, FOREIGN KEY \u2192 users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE | Session owner |\n| session_token | VARCHAR(500) | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | Session token |\n| expires_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL | Session expiration |\n| last_activity | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Last activity time |\n| ip_address | VARCHAR(45) | NULL | Client IP address |\n| user_agent | VARCHAR(500) | NULL | Client user agent |\n| created_at | TIMESTAMP | NOT NULL, DEFAULT NOW() | Creation timestamp |\n\n**PostgreSQL DDL:**\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE sessions (\n    id UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT uuid_generate_v4(),\n    user_id UUID NOT NULL REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,\n    session_token VARCHAR(500) NOT NULL UNIQUE,\n    expires_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,\n    last_activity TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),\n    ip_address VARCHAR(45),\n    user_agent VARCHAR(500),\n    created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_user_id ON sessions(user_id);\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_token ON sessions(session_token);\nCREATE INDEX idx_sessions_expires_at ON sessions(expires_at);\n```\n\n---\n\n## Database Constraints and Rules\n\n### Referential Integrity\n- **ON DELETE CASCADE:** When a user is deleted, all their TODOs are automatically deleted\n- **Foreign Key Constraints:** Ensure todos always reference valid users\n\n### Data Validation\n- **CHECK Constraints:** Ensure priority values are valid ('low', 'medium', 'high')\n- **NOT NULL Constraints:** Enforce required fields\n- **UNIQUE Constraints:** Prevent duplicate emails\n\n### Data Types\n- **UUID:** For all primary keys (better for distributed systems, security)\n- **VARCHAR:** For bounded text fields\n- **TEXT:** For unlimited text (descriptions)\n- **TIMESTAMP:** For all datetime fields (with timezone support)\n- **BOOLEAN:** For binary flags\n\n---\n\n## Query Patterns and Optimization\n\n### Common Queries\n\n**1. User Login:**\n```sql\nSELECT id, email, username, password_hash\nFROM users\nWHERE email = $1;\n```\n- **Index Used:** `idx_users_email` (unique index)\n- **Performance:** O(1) lookup\n\n**2. Get User's TODOs:**\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1\nORDER BY created_at DESC\nLIMIT 50 OFFSET 0;\n```\n- **Index Used:** `idx_todos_user_created_at`\n- **Performance:** Efficient with index\n\n**3. Filter Active TODOs:**\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1 AND completed = false\nORDER BY due_date ASC NULLS LAST;\n```\n- **Index Used:** `idx_todos_user_completed`, `idx_todos_user_due_date`\n- **Performance:** Efficient with composite index\n\n**4. Get TODO Statistics:**\n```sql\nSELECT\n    COUNT(*) as total,\n    COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE completed = true) as completed_count,\n    COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE completed = false) as active_count,\n User email address |\n| username | VARCHAR(50) | NOT NULL, UNIQUE | - | Unique username |\n| password_hash | VARCHAR(255) | NOT NULL | - | Bcrypt hashed password |\n| is_active | BOOLEAN | NOT NULL | Database Functions and Triggers\n\n### 5.1 Updated At Trigger (PostgreSQL)\n\n**Purpose:** Automatically update `updated_at` timestamp on row modification\n\n```sql\n-- Create trigger function\nCREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column()\nRETURNS TRIGGER AS $$\nBEGIN\n    NEW.updated_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP;\n    RETURN NEW;\nEND;\n$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;\n\n-- Apply to users table\nCREATE TRIGGER update_users_updated_at\n    BEFORE UPDATE ON users\n    FOR EACH ROW\n    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();\n\n-- Apply to todos table\nCREATE TRIGGER update_todos_updated_at\n    BEFORE UPDATE ON todos\n    FOR EACH ROW\n    EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at_column();\n```\n\n### 5.2 User Statistics View (Optional)\n\n**Purpose:** Quick access to user TODO statistics\n\n```sql\n-- Create materialized view for user statistics\nCREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW user_todo_stats AS\nSELECT\n    u.id AS user_id,\n    u.username,\n    u.email,\n    COUNT(t.id) AS total_todos,\n    COUNT(CASE WHEN t.is_completed = TRUE THEN 1 END) AS completed_todos,\n    COUNT(CASE WHEN t.is_completed = FALSE THEN 1 END) AS pending_todos,\n    COUNT(CASE WHEN t.priority = 'high' THEN 1 END) AS high_priority_todos,\n    MAX(t.created_at) AS last_todo_created_at\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN todos t ON u.id = t.user_id\nGROUP BY u.id, u.username, u.email;\n\n-- Create index on materialized view\nCREATE INDEX idx_user_todo_stats_user_id ON user_todo_stats(user_id);\n\n-- Refresh materialized view (run periodically or after bulk operations)\n-- REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW user_todo_stats;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Indexes Strategy\n\n### 6.1 Index Purpose\n\n| Table | Index | Columns | Purpose |\n|-------|-------|---------|---------|\n| users | idx_users_email | email | Fast user lookup during login |\n| users | idx_users_username | username | Username uniqueness and search |\n| users | idx_users_is_active | is_active | Filter active users |\n| todos | idx_todos_user_id | user_id | Fast retrieval of user's TODOs |\n| todos | idx_todos_is_completed | is_completed | Filter by completion status |\n| todos | idx_todos_priority | priority | Filter by priority |\n| todos | idx_todos_user_completed | user_id, is_completed | Combined filter queries |\n| todos | idx_todos_user_priority | user_id, priority | Priority-based user queries |\n| todos | idx_todos_search | title, description | Full-text search |\n\n### 6.2 Index Maintenance\n\n```sql\n-- Analyze tables for query optimization (PostgreSQL)\nANALYZE users;\nANALYZE todos;\n\n-- Reindex if necessary\nREINDEX TABLE users;\nREINDEX TABLE todos;\n\n-- Check index usage\nSELECT\n    schemaname,\n    tablename,\n    indexname,\n    idx_scan,\n    idx_tup_read,\n    idx_tup_fetch\nFROM pg_stat_user_indexes\nORDER BY idx_scan ASC;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Common Queries\n\n### 7.1 User Authentication\n\n```sql\n-- Find user by email for login\nSELECT id, email, username, password_hash, is_active\nFROM users\nWHERE email = $1 AND is_active = TRUE;\n\n-- Update last login time\nUPDATE users\nSET last_login_at = CURRENT_TIMESTAMP\nWHERE id = $1;\n```\n\n### 7.2 TODO Operations\n\n**Get User's TODOs with Filtering:**\n```sql\nSELECT\n    id,\n    title,\n    description,\n    is_completed,\n    priority,\n    due_date,\n    created_at,\n    updated_at\nFROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1\n    AND ($2::BOOLEAN IS NULL OR is_completed = $2)  -- Filter by status\n    AND ($3::priority_level IS NULL OR priority = $3)  -- Filter by priority\nORDER BY\n    CASE WHEN $4 = 'priority' THEN\n        CASE priority\n            WHEN 'high' THEN 1\n            WHEN 'medium' THEN 2\n            WHEN 'low' THEN 3\n        END\n    END,\n    created_at DESC\nLIMIT $5 OFFSET $6;  -- Pagination\n```\n\n**Count User's TODOs:**\n```sql\nSELECT COUNT(*)\nFROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1\n    AND ($2::BOOLEAN IS NULL OR is_completed = $2);\n```\n\n**Create TODO:**\n```sql\nINSERT INTO todos (user_id, title, description, priority, due_date)\nVALUES ($1, $2, $3, $4, $5)\nRETURNING *;\n```\n\n**Update TODO:**\n```sql\nUPDATE todos\nSET\n    title = COALESCE($3, title),\n    description = COALESCE($4, description),\n    priority = COALESCE($5, priority),\n    is_completed = COALESCE($6, is_completed),\n    due_date = COALESCE($7, due_date)\nWHERE id = $1 AND user_id = $2\nRETURNING *;\n```\n\n**Delete TODO:**\n```sql\nDELETE FROM todos\nWHERE id = $1 AND user_id = $2\nRETURNING id;\n```\n\n### 7.3 Search Queries\n\n**Full-text Search (PostgreSQL):**\n```sql\nSELECT\n    id,\n    title,\n    description,\n    priority,\n    is_completed,\n    ts_rank(\n        to_tsvector('english', title || ' ' || COALESCE(description, '')),\n        plainto_tsquery('english', $2)\n    ) AS rank\nFROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1\n    AND to_tsvector('english', title || ' ' || COALESCE(description, ''))\n        @@ plainto_tsquery('english', $2)\nORDER BY rank DESC, created_at DESC\nLIMIT 20;\n```\n\n**Full-text Search (MySQL):**\n```sql\nSELECT\n    id,\n    title,\n    description,\n    priority,\n    is_completed,\n    MATCH(title, description) AGAINST($2 IN NATURAL LANGUAGE MODE) AS relevance\nFROM todos\nWHERE user_id = $1\n    AND MATCH(title, description) AGAINST($2 IN NATURAL LANGUAGE MODE)\nORDER BY relevance DESC, created_at DESC\nLIMIT 20;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Performance Optimization\n\n### 10.1 Connection Pooling Configuration\n\n**Node.js (Sequelize/Prisma):**\n```javascript\n{\n  pool: {\n    min: 5,\n    max: 20,\n    acquire: 30000,\n    idle: 10000\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Python (SQLAlchemy):**\n```python\nengine = create_engine(\n    DATABASE_URL,\n    pool_size=10,\n    max_overflow=10,\n    pool_pre_ping=True\n)\n```\n\n### 10.2 Query Optimization Tips\n\n1. Always use indexes for foreign keys\n2. Use `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` to check query performance\n3. Avoid `SELECT *`, specify needed columns\n4. Use pagination for large result sets\n5. Consider materialized views for complex aggregations\n6. Use connection pooling\n7. Batch inserts when possible\n\n### 10.3 Monitoring Queries\n\n```sql\n-- Check slow queries (PostgreSQL)\nSELECT\n    query,\n    calls,\n    total_time,\n    mean_time,\n    max_time\nFROM pg_stat_statements\nORDER BY mean_time DESC\nLIMIT 10;\n\n-- Check table sizes\nSELECT\n    tablename,\n    pg_size_pretty(pg_total_relation_size(schemaname||'.'||tablename)) AS size\nFROM pg_tables\nWHERE schemaname = 'public'\nORDER BY pg_total_relation_size(schemaname||'.'||tablename) DESC;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Backup and Recovery\n\n### 11.1 Backup Strategy\n\n**Full Backup (PostgreSQL):**\n```bash\n# Backup entire database\npg_dump -h localhost -U postgres -d todo_app -F c -b -v -f \"backup_$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S).dump\"\n\n# Restore from backup\npg_restore -h localhost -U postgres -d todo_app -v \"backup_20251011_120000.dump\"\n```\n\n**Scheduled Backups:**\n```bash\n# Daily backup at 2 AM (cron job)\n0 2 * * * /usr/local/bin/backup_database.sh\n```\n\n### 11.2 Point-in-Time Recovery\n\nEnable WAL archiving for PostgreSQL:\n```ini\n# postgresql.conf\nwal_level = replica\narchive_mode = on\narchive_command = 'cp %p /var/lib/postgresql/wal_archive/%f'\n```\n\n---\n\n## 12. Security Considerations\n\n### 12.1 Database Security Checklist\n\n- [ ] Use strong database passwords\n- [ ] Limit database user privileges\n- [ ] Enable SSL/TLS for connections\n- [ ] Regular security updates\n- [ ] Audit logging enabled\n- [ ] Backup encryption\n- [ ] Network firewall rules\n- [ ] No default ports in production\n\n### 12.2 Application User Permissions\n\n```sql\n-- Create application user with limited permissions\nCREATE USER todo_app_user WITH PASSWORD 'strong_password';\n\n-- Grant only necessary permissions\nGRANT CONNECT ON DATABASE todo_app TO todo_app_user;\nGRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA public TO todo_app_user;\nGRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON users, todos TO todo_app_user;\nGRANT USAGE, SELECT ON ALL SEQUENCES IN SCHEMA public TO todo_app_user;\n\n-- Revoke unnecessary permissions\nREVOKE CREATE ON SCHEMA public FROM todo_app_user;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 13. Promise<string>\n\n  // Compare password with hash\n  comparePassword(password: string, hash: string): Promise<boolean>\n}\n```\n\n**Dependencies:**\n- UserRepository (data access)\n- JWTService Middleware Components\n\n### 4.1 Authentication Middleware\n\n**Purpose:** Verify JWT token and attach user to request\n\n```typescript\n// auth.middleware.js\nasync function authenticateJWT(req, res, next) {\n  try {\n    const token = extractTokenFromHeader(req.headers.authorization)\n\n    if (!token) {\n      throw new UnauthorizedError('No token provided')\n    }\n\n    const payload = await jwtService.verifyAccessToken(token)\n\n    // Attach user to request\n    req.user = {\n      id: payload.userId,\n      email: payload.email\n    }\n\n    next()\n  } catch (error) {\n    next(new UnauthorizedError('Invalid token'))\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### 4.2 Validation Middleware\n\n**Purpose:** Validate request data against schema\n\n```typescript\n// validation.middleware.js\nfunction validate(schema, property = 'body') {\n  return (req, res, next) => {\n    const { error, value } = schema.validate(req[property], {\n      abortEarly: false,\n      stripUnknown: true\n    })\n\n    if (error) {\n      const errors = error.details.map(detail => ({\n        field: detail.path.join('.'),\n        message: detail.message\n      }))\n\n      return next(new ValidationError('Invalid input', errors))\n    }\n\n    req[property] = value\n    next()\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### 4.3 Error Handler Middleware\n\n**Purpose:** Centralized error handling\n\n```typescript\n// error.middleware.js\nfunction errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {\n  logger.error({\n    message: err.message,\n    stack: err.stack,\n    requestId: req.id,\n    path: req.path\n  })\n\n  // Determine error type and response\n  const statusCode = err.statusCode || 500\n  const response = {\n    success: false,\n    error: {\n      code: err.code || 'INTERNAL_ERROR',\n      message: err.message || 'Internal server error',\n      ...(err.details && { details: err.details })\n    },\n    metadata: {\n      timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n      requestId: req.id\n    }\n  }\n\n  res.status(statusCode).json(response)\n}\n```\n\n### 4.4 Rate Limiting Middleware\n\n**Purpose:** Prevent abuse\n\n```typescript\n// rate-limit.middleware.js\nconst rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit')\n\n// Authentication endpoints\nconst authLimiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 60 * 1000, // 1 minute\n  max: 5, // 5 requests per window\n  message: {\n    success: false,\n    error: {\n      code: 'RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED',\n      message: 'Too many requests, please try again later'\n    }\n  }\n})\n\n// General API endpoints\nconst apiLimiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 60 * 1000,\n  max: 100,\n  keyGenerator: (req) => req.user?.id || req.ip\n})\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Dependency Injection\n\n### 8.1 Service Container Pattern\n\n```typescript\n// container.js\nclass Container {\n  constructor() {\n    this.services = new Map()\n  }\n\n  register(name, factory) {\n    this.services.set(name, { factory, instance: null })\n  }\n\n  get(name) {\n    const service = this.services.get(name)\n\n    if (!service) {\n      throw new Error(`Service ${name} not found`)\n    }\n\n    if (!service.instance) {\n      service.instance = service.factory(this)\n    }\n\n    return service.instance\n  }\n}\n\n// Setup\nconst container = new Container()\n\n// Register repositories\ncontainer.register('userRepository', () => new UserRepository(db))\ncontainer.register('todoRepository', () => new TodoRepository(db))\n\n// Register services\ncontainer.register('authService', (c) =>\n  new AuthService(c.get('userRepository'), c.get('jwtService'))\n)\ncontainer.register('todoService', (c) =>\n  new TodoService(c.get('todoRepository'))\n)\n\nexport default container\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. State Management Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Context-Based State Management\n\n**Auth Context:**\n```typescript\ninterface AuthContextType {\n  user: User | null;\n  isAuthenticated: boolean;\n  isLoading: boolean;\n  login: (email: string, password: string) => Promise<void>;\n  register: (data: RegisterData) => Promise<void>;\n  logout: () => Promise<void>;\n  refreshToken: () => Promise<void>;\n}\n```\n\n**Todo Context:**\n```typescript\ninterface TodoContextType {\n  todos: Todo[];\n  isLoading: boolean;\n  error: Error | null;\n  filters: TodoFilters;\n  pagination: PaginationInfo;\n  fetchTodos: (filters?: TodoFilters) => Promise<void>;\n  createTodo: (data: CreateTodoData) => Promise<void>;\n  updateTodo: (id: string, data: UpdateTodoData) => Promise<void>;\n  deleteTodo: (id: string) => Promise<void>;\n  toggleComplete: (id: string) => Promise<void>;\n  setFilters: (filters: TodoFilters) => void;\n}\n```\n\n**Notification Context:**\n```typescript\ninterface NotificationContextType {\n  notifications: Notification[];\n  showNotification: (message: string, type: NotificationType) => void;\n  hideNotification: (id: string) => void;\n}\n```\n\n### 3.2 State Management Strategy\n\n**Global State (Context):**\n- User authentication state\n- User profile data\n- Theme preferences\n- Notifications/toasts\n\n**Local State (Component useState):**\n- Form inputs\n- UI toggles (modals, dropdowns)\n- Loading states for specific actions\n- Validation errors\n\n**Server State (React Query alternative with Context):**\n- TODO list data\n- Cached API responses\n- Optimistic updates\n\n---\n\n## 4. Routing Architecture\n\n### 4.1 Route Structure\n\n```typescript\n// Public Routes\n/                       \u2192 Landing/Home page (redirects to /login if not authenticated)\n/login                  \u2192 Login page\n/register               \u2192 Registration page\n/forgot-password        \u2192 Password recovery page\n\n// Protected Routes (requires authentication)\n/dashboard              \u2192 Dashboard/Home page (TODO list)\n/todos                  \u2192 TODO list page\n/todos/new              \u2192 Create new TODO\n/todos/:id              \u2192 View TODO detail\n/todos/:id/edit         \u2192 Edit TODO\n/profile                \u2192 User profile page\n/settings               \u2192 User settings page\n\n// Error Routes\n/404                    \u2192 Not found page\n/403                    \u2192 Forbidden page\n/500                    \u2192 Server error page\n```\n\n### 4.2 Route Protection\n\n```typescript\ninterface ProtectedRouteProps {\n  children: React.ReactNode;\n  redirectTo?: string;\n}\n\n// Protected Route wrapper\n<Route element={<ProtectedRoute />}>\n  <Route path=\"/dashboard\" element={<DashboardPage />} />\n  <Route path=\"/todos\" element={<TodoListPage />} />\n  {/* ... other protected routes */}\n</Route>\n\n// Public only routes (redirect if authenticated)\n<Route element={<PublicOnlyRoute />}>\n  <Route path=\"/login\" element={<LoginPage />} />\n  <Route path=\"/register\" element={<RegisterPage />} />\n</Route>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Responsive Design Strategy\n\n### 8.1 Mobile-First Approach\n\n**Breakpoint Strategy:**\n```css\n/* Mobile First (Default) */\n.container { width: 100%; }\n\n/* Tablet and up */\n@media (min-width: 768px) {\n  .container { width: 750px; }\n}\n\n/* Desktop and up */\n@media (min-width: 1024px) {\n  .container { width: 960px; }\n}\n\n/* Large Desktop and up */\n@media (min-width: 1280px) {\n  .container { width: 1200px; }\n}\n```\n\n### 8.2 Responsive Layout Patterns\n\n**Mobile (< 768px):**\n- Single column layout\n- Full-width components\n- Bottom navigation (if applicable)\n- Collapsible sidebar\n- Stack cards vertically\n\n**Tablet (768px - 1024px):**\n- Two-column layout for TODO list\n- Side drawer for filters\n- Floating action button\n\n**Desktop (> 1024px):**\n- Three-column layout option\n- Persistent sidebar\n- Multi-panel views\n- Keyboard shortcuts\n\n---\n\n## 9. Form Management\n\n### 9.1 Form Architecture\n\n**Using React Hook Form + Zod:**\n\n```typescript\n// Example: Login Form Schema\nimport { z } from 'zod';\nimport { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';\nimport { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod';\n\nconst loginSchema = z.object({\n  email: z.string().email('Invalid email address'),\n  password: z.string().min(1, 'Password is required'),\n});\n\ntype LoginFormData = z.infer<typeof loginSchema>;\n\n// In component\nconst {\n  register,\n  handleSubmit,\n  formState: { errors, isSubmitting },\n} = useForm<LoginFormData>({\n  resolver: zodResolver(loginSchema),\n});\n```\n\n### 9.2 Validation Schemas\n\n**Register Form Schema:**\n```typescript\nconst registerSchema = z.object({\n  email: z.string().email('Invalid email address'),\n  username: z\n    .string()\n    .min(3, 'Username must be at least 3 characters')\n    .max(50, 'Username must be less than 50 characters')\n    .regex(/^[a-zA-Z0-9_]+$/, 'Username can only contain letters, numbers, and underscores'),\n  password: z\n    .string()\n    .min(8, 'Password must be at least 8 characters')\n    .regex(/[A-Z]/, 'Password must contain at least one uppercase letter')\n    .regex(/[a-z]/, 'Password must contain at least one lowercase letter')\n    .regex(/[0-9]/, 'Password must contain at least one number'),\n  confirmPassword: z.string(),\n}).refine((data) => data.password === data.confirmPassword, {\n  message: \"Passwords don't match\",\n  path: ['confirmPassword'],\n});\n```\n\n**Todo Form Schema:**\n```typescript\nconst todoSchema = z.object({\n  title: z\n    .string()\n    .min(1, 'Title is required')\n    .max(255, 'Title must be less than 255 characters'),\n  description: z\n    .string()\n    .max(2000, 'Description must be less than 2000 characters')\n    .optional(),\n  priority: z.enum(['low', 'medium', 'high']).optional(),\n  dueDate: z.string().optional().refine(\n    (date) => !date || new Date(date) > new Date(),\n    { message: 'Due date must be in the future' }\n  ),\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Custom Hooks Architecture\n\n### 10.1 Data Fetching Hooks\n\n**useAuth Hook:**\n```typescript\nexport function useAuth() {\n  const context = useContext(AuthContext);\n  if (!context) {\n    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within AuthProvider');\n  }\n  return context;\n}\n```\n\n**useTodos Hook:**\n```typescript\nexport function useTodos() {\n  const context = useContext(TodoContext);\n  if (!context) {\n    throw new Error('useTodos must be used within TodoProvider');\n  }\n  return context;\n}\n```\n\n### 10.2 Utility Hooks\n\n**useDebounce Hook:**\n```typescript\nexport function useDebounce<T>(value: T, delay: number): T {\n  const [debouncedValue, setDebouncedValue] = useState<T>(value);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const handler = setTimeout(() => {\n      setDebouncedValue(value);\n    }, delay);\n\n    return () => {\n      clearTimeout(handler);\n    };\n  }, [value, delay]);\n\n  return debouncedValue;\n}\n```\n\n**useLocalStorage Hook:**\n```typescript\nexport function useLocalStorage<T>(\n  key: string,\n  initialValue: T\n): [T, (value: T) => void] {\n  // Implementation\n}\n```\n\n**useMediaQuery Hook:**\n```typescript\nexport function useMediaQuery(query: string): boolean {\n  // Implementation for responsive design\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Performance Optimization\n\n### 11.1 Code Splitting Strategy\n\n**Route-based Code Splitting:**\n```typescript\nimport { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';\n\n// Lazy load route components\nconst TodoListPage = lazy(() => import('./pages/TodoListPage'));\nconst TodoDetailPage = lazy(() => import('./pages/TodoDetailPage'));\nconst UserProfilePage = lazy(() => import('./pages/UserProfilePage'));\n\n// In router\n<Suspense fallback={<PageLoader />}>\n  <Routes>\n    <Route path=\"/todos\" element={<TodoListPage />} />\n    <Route path=\"/todos/:id\" element={<TodoDetailPage />} />\n    <Route path=\"/profile\" element={<UserProfilePage />} />\n  </Routes>\n</Suspense>\n```\n\n### 11.2 Memoization Strategy\n\n**Component Memoization:**\n```typescript\n// Memoize expensive components\nconst TodoItem = React.memo(TodoItemComponent);\nconst TodoList = React.memo(TodoListComponent);\n\n// Memoize callbacks\nconst handleToggle = useCallback((id: string) => {\n  toggleTodo(id);\n}, [toggleTodo]);\n\n// Memoize computed values\nconst filteredTodos = useMemo(() => {\n  return todos.filter(todo => /* filter logic */);\n}, [todos, filters]);\n```\n\n### 11.3 Optimization Techniques\n\n1. **Virtual Scrolling:** For long TODO lists (if > 100 items)\n2. **Image Optimization:** Lazy loading, responsive images\n3. **Bundle Size:** Tree shaking, code splitting\n4. **Caching:** Service worker, cache API responses\n5. **Debouncing:** Search inputs, API calls\n6. **Throttling:** Scroll events, resize events\n\n---\n\n## 12. Accessibility (a11y) Guidelines\n\n### 12.1 ARIA Attributes\n\n```typescript\n// Button with loading state\n<button\n  type=\"submit\"\n  disabled={isLoading}\n  aria-busy={isLoading}\n  aria-label=\"Submit form\"\n>\n  {isLoading ? Component-specific types (if complex)\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 index.ts                   # Barrel export\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. State Management Architecture\n\n### 5.1 State Categories\n\n#### Local State\n- **Scope:** Single component\n- **Implementation:** `useState`, `useReducer`\n- **Examples:** Form inputs, UI toggles, local loading states\n\n#### Shared UI State\n- **Scope:** Multiple components\n- **Implementation:** React Context API\n- **Examples:** Auth state, theme, sidebar open/close, notifications\n\n#### Server State\n- **Scope:** Data from API\n- **Implementation:** React Query (TanStack Query)\n- **Examples:** Resources, user data, cached API responses\n\n### 5.2 Context Providers\n\n#### AuthContext\n\n```typescript\n// src/context/AuthContext.tsx\n\ninterface AuthState {\n  user: User | null;\n  isAuthenticated: boolean;\n  isLoading: boolean;\n}\n\ninterface AuthContextValue extends AuthState {\n  login: (credentials: LoginCredentials) => Promise<void>;\n  register: (data: RegisterData) => Promise<void>;\n  logout: () => Promise<void>;\n  checkAuth: () => Promise<void>;\n}\n\nconst AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue | undefined>(undefined);\n\nexport function AuthProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {\n  const [state, setState] = useState<AuthState>({\n    user: null,\n    isAuthenticated: false,\n    isLoading: true,\n  });\n\n  // Implementation...\n\n  return (\n    <AuthContext.Provider value={value}>\n      {children}\n    </AuthContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\nexport function useAuth() {\n  const context = useContext(AuthContext);\n  if (!context) {\n    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within AuthProvider');\n  }\n  return context;\n}\n```\n\n#### UIContext\n\n```typescript\n// src/context/UIContext.tsx\n\ninterface UIState {\n  sidebarOpen: boolean;\n  theme: 'light' | 'dark';\n}\n\ninterface UIContextValue extends UIState {\n  toggleSidebar: () => void;\n  setTheme: (theme: 'light' | 'dark') => void;\n}\n```\n\n#### ToastContext\n\n```typescript\n// src/context/ToastContext.tsx\n\ninterface Toast {\n  id: string;\n  message: string;\n  type: 'success' | 'error' | 'warning' | 'info';\n}\n\ninterface ToastContextValue {\n  toasts: Toast[];\n  showToast: (message: string, type: Toast['type']) => void;\n  hideToast: (id: string) => void;\n}\n```\n\n### 5.3 React Query Configuration\n\n```typescript\n// src/lib/queryClient.ts\n\nimport { QueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';\n\nexport const queryClient = new QueryClient({\n  defaultOptions: {\n    queries: {\n      retry: 1,\n      refetchOnWindowFocus: false,\n      staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes\n      cacheTime: 10 * 60 * 1000, // 10 minutes\n    },\n    mutations: {\n      retry: 0,\n    },\n  },\n});\n```\n\n**Query Keys Convention:**\n- `['resources']` - List of resources\n- `['resources', id]` - Single resource\n- `['auth', 'user']` - Current user\n\n---\n\n## 6. Routing Architecture\n\n### 6.1 Route Structure\n\n```typescript\n// src/routes/index.tsx\n\nimport { createBrowserRouter, Navigate } from 'react-router-dom';\n\nexport const router = createBrowserRouter([\n  {\n    path: '/',\n    element: <Navigate to=\"/dashboard\" replace />,\n  },\n  {\n    path: '/login',\n    element: <LoginPage />,\n  },\n  {\n    path: '/register',\n    element: <RegisterPage />,\n  },\n  {\n    path: '/dashboard',\n    element: (\n      <ProtectedRoute>\n        <AppLayout>\n          <DashboardPage />\n        </AppLayout>\n      </ProtectedRoute>\n    ),\n  },\n  {\n    path: '/resources',\n    children: [\n      {\n        path: 'new',\n        element: (\n          <ProtectedRoute>\n            <AppLayout>\n              <CreateResourcePage />\n            </AppLayout>\n          </ProtectedRoute>\n        ),\n      },\n      {\n        path: ':id',\n        element: (\n          <ProtectedRoute>\n            <AppLayout>\n              <ResourceDetailPage />\n            </AppLayout>\n          </ProtectedRoute>\n        ),\n      },\n      {\n        path: ':id/edit',\n        element: (\n          <ProtectedRoute>\n            <AppLayout>\n              <EditResourcePage />\n            </AppLayout>\n          </ProtectedRoute>\n        ),\n      },\n    ],\n  },\n  {\n    path: '/403',\n    element: <UnauthorizedPage />,\n  },\n  {\n    path: '*',\n    element: <NotFoundPage />,\n  },\n]);\n```\n\n### 6.2 Protected Route Implementation\n\n```typescript\n// src/components/auth/ProtectedRoute/ProtectedRoute.tsx\n\nimport { Navigate, useLocation } from 'react-router-dom';\nimport { useAuth } from '@/context/AuthContext';\nimport { LoadingSpinner } from '@/components/feedback/LoadingSpinner';\n\ninterface ProtectedRouteProps {\n  children: React.ReactNode;\n  redirectTo?: string;\n}\n\nexport function ProtectedRoute({\n  children,\n  redirectTo = '/login'\n}: ProtectedRouteProps) {\n  const { isAuthenticated, isLoading } = useAuth();\n  const location = useLocation();\n\n  if (isLoading) {\n    return <LoadingSpinner />;\n  }\n\n  if (!isAuthenticated) {\n    return <Navigate to={redirectTo} state={{ from: location }} replace />;\n  }\n\n  return <>{children}</>;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Data Flow Architecture\n\n### 7.1 Authentication Flow\n\n```\n1. User submits login form\n   \u2193\n2. LoginForm calls useLogin hook\n   \u2193\n3. useLogin hook calls authService.login()\n   \u2193\n4. authService makes API call\n   \u2193\n5. On success, token stored in tokenManager\n   \u2193\n6. AuthContext updated with user data\n   \u2193\n7. User redirected to dashboard\n   \u2193\n8. Protected routes now accessible\n```\n\n### 7.2 Resource CRUD Flow\n\n```\nCreate Resource:\n1. User fills ResourceForm\n   \u2193\n2. Form validated with Zod schema\n   \u2193\n3. Form calls onSubmit with data\n   \u2193\n4. Page calls useCreateResource hook\n   \u2193\n5. Hook calls resourceService.createResource()\n   \u2193\n6. API request with auth token\n   \u2193\n7. On success, React Query invalidates cache\n   \u2193\n8. Resource list refetches automatically\n   \u2193\n9. Success toast shown\n   \u2193\n10. User redirected to resource detail\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Error Handling Architecture\n\n### 8.1 Error Boundaries\n\n```typescript\n// src/components/common/ErrorBoundary/ErrorBoundary.tsx\n\nclass ErrorBoundary extends React.Component<Props, State> {\n  state = { hasError: false, error: null };\n\n  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error) {\n    return { hasError: true, error };\n  }\n\n  componentDidCatch(error: Error, errorInfo: ErrorInfo) {\n    console.error('Error caught by boundary:', error, errorInfo);\n  }\n\n  render() {\n    if (this.state.hasError) {\n      return <ErrorFallback error={this.state.error} />;\n    }\n\n    return this.props.children;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### 8.2 API Error Handling\n\n```\n1. API request fails\n   \u2193\n2. Axios interceptor catches error\n   \u2193\n3. Error parsed by errorHandler utility\n   \u2193\n4. 401 \u2192 Clear token, redirect to login\n   \u2193\n5. 403 \u2192 Show forbidden message\n   \u2193\n6. 4xx/5xx \u2192 Show user-friendly message\n   \u2193\n7. Network error \u2192 Show offline message\n   \u2193\n8. Display error via Toast or ErrorMessage component\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Performance Optimization\n\n### 9.1 Code Splitting\n\n```typescript\n// Lazy load pages\nconst DashboardPage = lazy(() => import('@/pages/DashboardPage'));\nconst ResourceDetailPage = lazy(() => import('@/pages/ResourceDetailPage'));\n\n// Usage\n<Suspense fallback={<LoadingSpinner />}>\n  <DashboardPage />\n</Suspense>\n```\n\n### 9.2 Memoization\n\n```typescript\n// Memoize expensive computations\nconst sortedResources = useMemo(\n  () => resources.sort((a, b) => b.createdAt - a.createdAt),\n  [resources]\n);\n\n// Memoize callbacks\nconst handleDelete = useCallback(\n  (id: string) => {\n    deleteResource(id);\n  },\n  [deleteResource]\n);\n\n// Memoize components\nexport const ResourceCard = memo(ResourceCardComponent);\n```\n\n### 9.3 Virtualization\n\nFor long lists, use virtualization:\n```typescript\nimport { FixedSizeList } from 'react-window';\n\n<FixedSizeList\n  height={600}\n  itemCount={resources.length}\n  itemSize={120}\n  width=\"100%\"\n>\n  {Row}\n</FixedSizeList>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Security Architecture\n\n### 10.1 Authentication Security\n\n- JWT tokens stored in memory (not localStorage by default)\n- Tokens never exposed in URLs\n- HTTPS only in production\n- Token validation before each request\n- Auto-logout on token expiration\n\n### 10.2 Input Sanitization\n\n```typescript\n// Sanitize user inputs\nimport DOMPurify from 'dompurify';\n\nconst sanitizedInput = DOMPurify.sanitize(userInput);\n```\n\n### 10.3 Content Security Policy\n\n```html\n<!-- index.html -->\n<meta http-equiv=\"Content-Security-Policy\"\n      content=\"default-src 'self';\n               script-src 'self';\n               style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline';\n               img-src 'self' data: https:;\">\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Zakas](https://humanwhocodes.com)\n\nIf you find this useful, please consider supporting my work with a [donation](https://humanwhocodes.com/donate).\n\n## Overview\n\nA JavaScript object merge/validation utility where you can define a different merge and validation strategy for each key. This is helpful when you need to validate complex data structures and then merge them in a way that is more complex than `Object.assign()`.\n\n## Installation\n\nYou can install using either npm:\n\n```\nnpm install @humanwhocodes/object-schema\n```\n\nOr Yarn:\n\n```\nyarn add @humanwhocodes/object-schema\n```\n\n## Usage\n\nUse CommonJS to get access to the `ObjectSchema` merge(value1, value2) {\n            return value1.concat(value2);\n        },\n        validate(value) {\n            if (!Array.isArray(value)) {\n                throw new Error(\"Expected versions to be an array.\");\n            }\n        }\n    }\n});\n\nconst record1 = {\n    downloads: 25,\n    versions: [\n        \"v1.0.0\",\n        \"v1.1.0\",\n        \"v1.2.0\"\n    ]\n};\n\nconst record2 = {\n    downloads: 125,\n    versions: [\n        \"v2.0.0\",\n        \"v2.1.0\",\n        \"v3.0.0\"\n    ]\n};\n\n// make sure the records are valid\nschema.validate(record1);\nschema.validate(record2);\n\n// merge together (schema.merge() accepts any number of objects)\nconst result = schema.merge(record1, record2);\n\n// result looks like this:\n\nconst result = {\n    downloads: 75,\n    versions: [\n        \"v1.0.0\",\n        \"v1.1.0\",\n        \"v1.2.0\",\n        \"v2.0.0\",\n        \"v2.1.0\",\n        \"v3.0.0\"\n    ]\n};\n```\n\n## Tips and Tricks\n\n### Named merge strategies\n\nInstead of specifying a `merge()` method, you can specify one of the following strings to use a default merge strategy:\n\n* `\"assign\"` - use `Object.assign()` to merge the two values into one object.\n* `\"overwrite\"` - the second value always replaces the first.\n* `\"replace\"` - the second value replaces the first if strategies\n\nInstead of specifying a `validate()` method, you can specify one of the following strings to use a default validation strategy:\n\n* `\"array\"` - value must be an array.\n* `\"boolean\"` - value must be a boolean.\n* `\"number\"` - value must be a number.\n* `\"object\"` - value must be an object.\n* `\"object?\"` - value must be an object or null.\n* `\"string\"` - \"string\"\n    }\n});\n```\n\n### Subschemas\n\nIf you are defining a key that is, itself, an object, you can simplify the process by using a subschema. Instead of defining `merge()` and `validate()`, assign a `schema` key that contains a schema definition, like this:\n\n```js\nconst schema = new ObjectSchema({\n    name: {\n        schema: {\n            first: {\n                merge: \"replace\",\n                validate: \"string\"\n            },\n            last: {\n                merge: \"replace\",\n                validate: \"string\"\n            }\n        }\n    }\n});\n\nschema.validate({\n    name: {\n        first: \"n\",\n        last: \"z\"\n    }\n});\n```\n\n### Remove Keys During Merge\n\nIf the merge strategy for a key returns `undefined`, then the key will not appear in the final object.       "generated_project/backend/node_modules/json-schema-traverse/README.md": "# json-schema-traverse\nTraverse JSON Schema passing each schema object to callback\n\n[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/epoberezkin/json-schema-traverse.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/epoberezkin/json-schema-traverse)\n[![npm version](https://badge.fury.io/js/json-schema-traverse.svg)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/json-schema-traverse)\n[![Coverage Status](https://coveralls.io/repos/github/epoberezkin/json-schema-traverse/badge.svg?branch=master)](https://coveralls.io/github/epoberezkin/json-schema-traverse?branch=master)\n\n\n## Install\n\n```\nnpm install json-schema-traverse\n```\n\n\n## Usage\n\n```javascript\nconst traverse = require('json-schema-traverse');\nconst schema = {\n  properties: {\n    foo: {type: 'string'},\n    bar: {type: 'integer'}\n  }\n};\n\ntraverse(schema, {cb});\n// cb is called 3 times with:\n// 1. root schema\n// 2. {type: 'string'}\n// 3. {type: 'integer'}\n\n// Or:\n\ntraverse(schema, {cb: {pre, post}});\n// pre is called 3 times with:\n// 1. root schema\n// 2. {type: 'string'}\n// 3. {type: 'integer'}\n//\n// post is called 3 times with:\n// 1. {type: 'string'}\n// 2. {type: 'integer'}\n// 3. root schema\n\n```\n\nCallback function `cb` is called for each schema object (not including draft-06 boolean schemas), including the root schema, in pre-order traversal. Schema references ($ref) are not resolved, they are passed as is.  Alternatively, you can pass a `{pre, post}` object as `cb`, and then `pre` will be called before traversing child elements, and `post` will be called after all child elements have been traversed.\n\nCallback is passed these parameters:\n\n- _schema_: the current schema object\n- _JSON pointer_: from the root schema to the current schema object\n- _root schema_: the schema passed to `traverse` object\n- _parent JSON pointer_: from the root schema to the parent schema object (see below)\n- _parent keyword_: the keyword inside which this schema appears (e.g. `properties`, `anyOf`, etc.)\n- _parent schema_: not necessarily parent object/array; in the example above the parent schema for `{type: 'string'}` is the root schema\n- _index/property_: index or property name in the array/object containing multiple schemas; in the example above for `{type: 'string'}` the property name is `'foo'`\n\n\n## Traverse objects in all unknown keywords\n\n```javascript\nconst traverse = require('json-schema-traverse');\nconst schema = {\n  mySchema: {\n    minimum: 1,\n    maximum: 2\n  }\n};\n\ntraverse(schema, {allKeys: true, cb});\n// cb is called 2 times with:\n// 1. root schema\n// 2. mySchema\n```\n\nWithout option `allKeys: true` callback will be called only with root schema.\n\n\n## License\n\n[MIT](https://github.com/epoberezkin/json-schema-traverse/blob/master/LICENSE)\n",
